column11: The scatter plot shows a red dominated homerun field. Almost evenly distributed with a slightly more concetration towards left field.

Here at AT&T Park we see a major concetration of both home and away homeruns across left field. This usually highlights the closer distance to homeplate that area of the field has over the right end, left field is 20 feet closer than right field.
Busch Stadium has equidistant center field to homeplate distances. The evenly distributed home and away homeruns from almost the entire distance of the field highlights this.
The long distance to direct center field limits the amount of homeruns hit there. Encouraging players to aim more right or left than usual.
A relatively new baseball field, Citi Field has a growing number of homeruns as the years go on.

With an almost equally distributed homerun rate across the field, the Philadelphia Phillies have had a very consistent homerun count on their home field, meaning the large drops in total homeruns are from the away teams.
Another Park with a center field farther from homeplate than the other areas of concetrated homeruns. With the Detroit Tigers responsible for on average half of the homeruns on the field.

Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies, has a large concentration of homeruns on both left-center and right-center field. However the homeruns tend to be more concentrated closer to the fence on right field as opposed to left.
Dodger Stadium has an almost even distribution of homeruns from both the home team, the LA Dodgers, and the away teams.

Fenway Park, home of the infamous "Green Monster," has a large mass of most runs on left field. However the homeruns on right field appear in almost a straight line, showing the length and difficulty of playing with the "Green Monster."
